Director of Criminal Investigation DCI is likely to charge Mombasa Governor Hassan Ali Joho with forgery of his KCSE certificate he allegedly used to secure admission at University of Nairobi.The detectives have also almost finalized investigation into how Joho may have used a KCSE result slip, with a mean grade of C+ to get admission to the University.The officers are interested on a result slip issued in Joho's name, claiming he sat for his secondary school examinations at Serani High School in 1992.Joho on Tuesday recorded a statement at Mombasa DCI, disowned the slip and insisted that he scored a D-, when he sat for the examination in 1993 and Serani High School.On Monday, the school defended Joho saying the governor was a bonafide student at the school.He said Joho was at the school from February 1990 and left in November 1993, having successfully sat his KCSE exams.The officers leading the investigation say the report recommending his prosecution will be forwarded the office of Director of Public Prosecutions for directionJoho says he is ready to defend himself in court over the allegation and accused the Jubilee government of intimidating him because of his political stand.Joho was with other leaders including Siaya Senator and lawyer James Orengo, woman representative Mishi Mboko, Kilifi Governor Amason Kingi and ODM secretary general Agnes Zani.Kingi accused the government of applying selective justice in Joho&rsquo;s case.